Speedy downloading: on compile, divide data into chunks ---
separate csv files. In general a chunk of data will be shown
onscreen at the same time, but we should not make chunks with
only 1 row e.g. for the WorldBank viz, geom_points should have
1 chunk per year, geom_text country labels sholuld have 1 chunk
per country, and geom_text year labels should have just 1 chunk
which covers all years. On page load, start downloading the first
chunk for each geom. After a chunk finishes downloading, start
downloading the next chunk for that geom, until all data is loaded,
even if it is not needed on screen right now. Also, start downloading
a chunk if we click on an unloaded subset that we need to show.
E.g. for geom_point start downloading the year=1960 chunk, then
the year=1961 chunk, but then if we clicked on year=2000, download
that one immediately and set the next chunk in the queue as year=2001.

Download progress table at the bottom of the plot.
- click a button to show or hide the entire table.
- starts shown, hides itself when everything is loaded.
- row for every geom.
- at least 3 columns: geom, total chunks, downloaded chunks.

Why does it take so much memory to compile large e.g. monkeys data?

